<div class="container">
    <h1>Server-Side Communication</h1>
    <p><strong>Server-side communication</strong> refers to operations that happen on the server in response to client requests. The server processes requests, interacts with databases or services, and sends back responses to the client.</p>

    <h2>Main Responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Processing Requests:</strong> Handling HTTP requests from clients (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE).</li>
        <li><strong>Business Logic:</strong> Executing server-side code to process data or perform actions.</li>
        <li><strong>Database Interaction:</strong> Reading from or writing to databases based on client requests.</li>
        <li><strong>Generating Responses:</strong> Sending HTML, JSON, or other data back to the client.</li>
        <li><strong>Security & Validation:</strong> Ensuring requests are valid and authenticated.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Simple API Endpoint (C# ASP.NET Core)</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Server-Side Code Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class UsersController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet("{id}")]
    public IActionResult GetUser(int id)
    {
        var user = _userService.GetUserById(id); // Fetch from database
        if(user == null)
            return NotFound();
        return Ok(user); // Return JSON response
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>In this example, the server receives a request for a user by ID, queries the database, and returns a JSON response to the client.</p>

